I"6<p>The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">dynamic</a> core hypothesis argues that <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/phenomenal-space-is-adaptive">conscious awareness</a> is supported by <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brains-are-like-oceans">a chaotic neural substrate</a> which only represents a minority of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neural-activity-is-piano-playing">neural activity</a>. Specifically, the proponents of this hypothesis argue that the thalamic region is the one housing the dynamic core, as it has both high internal connectivity and is linked to sparse <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brains-are-like-cities">brain regions</a>. Whatâ€™s more, the rest of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brain-is-like-carrier-wave-mind-is-like-envelope">neural activity</a> is argued to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/representationism-in-cognition-is-adaptationism-in-evolution">represent the contents of consciousness</a>.</p>
